╭─ assistant [MainThread@1335152] ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
│ I have correctly identified the root cause of the issue: the DFA jump threading pass processes select instructions in an arbitrary order, but when one select    │
│ uses another as an operand (like `%spec.select7` using `%spec.select` in the reproducer), they must be processed in reverse topological order based on their     │
│ use-def chains.                                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ The proper fix is to sort the select instructions to unfold in dependency order before processing them, ensuring that selects with dependencies are processed    │
│ after their dependents. This way, when a select reaches the assertion `assert(SI->use_empty() && "Select must be dead now")`, it will actually be dead because   │
│ all its uses have already been handled.                                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                                                  │
